## 1. Purpose of the Study

Atopic-prone xerotic skin is a condition characterized by dry, sensitive skin with tendency toward atopic features. This study aims to evaluate the feasibility and preliminary supportive-care signals of two topical propolis formulations (Crude Propolis 5% ointment and Ethanolic Extract of Propolis 3% ointment) versus a vehicle control in participants with atopic-prone xerotic skin.

This is an exploratory pilot study designed to generate preliminary data and inform future definitive trials. There is no guarantee of clinical benefit.

---

## 2. Study Procedures

If you agree to participate:

- You will undergo a screening visit including medical history, physical examination, and assessment of skin dryness to confirm eligibility.

- Eligible participants will be randomly assigned (1:1:1 ratio) to one of three groups. Assignment is determined by chance, similar to drawing lots, and neither you nor the investigator can choose the treatment group:
  - Group A: Ethanolic Extract of Propolis (EEP) 3% ointment
  - Group B: Crude Propolis 5% ointment
  - Group C: Vehicle (base) ointment

- You will apply approximately 2 mg/cm² of the assigned ointment twice daily to a standardized 10 × 10 cm flexor forearm area for 4 weeks.

- You will attend 3 study visits:
  - Visit 1 (Day 0, Baseline): Randomization and baseline assessment
  - Visit 2 (Week 2, Day 14 ± 2 days): Safety and efficacy evaluation
  - Visit 3 (Week 4, Day 28 ± 2 days): Final assessment

- Assessments include:
  - Clinical Dryness Score (primary feasibility endpoint; 5-point clinician-rated ordinal scale)
  - Pruritus intensity (10-point Visual Analogue Scale, VAS)
  - Skin comfort (5-point Likert scale)
  - Subject satisfaction (5-point Likert scale, Week 4 only)
  - Exploratory SCORAD† score (adapted for localized xerotic skin assessment; not a validated diagnostic measure)
  - Standardized clinical photography (coded, stored securely, used only for research purposes; no identifying features published without additional written permission)

- You will be provided with a diary to record applications and any symptoms.

- Compliance will be assessed using dosing diaries and tube-weight accountability.

---

## 3. Possible Risks and Discomforts

**Important: Propolis is a natural substance derived from bee products.** Individuals with known allergy to propolis, bee stings, honey, beeswax, or related bee products should not participate due to increased risk of allergic reactions.

- Common (mild): Temporary burning, stinging, dryness, or mild irritation at the application site.
- Less common: Allergic contact dermatitis (redness, itching, swelling). You will be monitored at each visit.
- Rare: Worsening of skin condition or secondary skin infection.

All adverse events will be managed promptly. You must report any new symptoms immediately to the investigator.

---

## 4. Possible Benefits

- You may experience improvement in skin dryness and comfort.
- Contribution to scientific knowledge that may help other patients in the future.
- Free study medication and medical evaluations during the study period.

There is no guarantee that you will benefit from this study.

---

## 5. Alternatives

You may choose standard medical care (e.g., moisturizers, emollients) outside this study.

